Shuffle → makes your data fair
Seed → makes your results consistent

Purpose: to measure whether your model generalizes to unseen data.

Train set teaches theta (model learns here).
Test set is held out and only used after training to evaluate real performance.
Without a test set, a low error could just mean the model fit the training data well, not that it will work on new houses.

If you split before shuffling, train/test might come from different parts of an ordered dataset.
Then train and test distributions can differ, giving unreliable learning/evaluation.

(axis= 0) compute down the rows -> per column
Spread = how far the values are from the average (mean)

big spread → large numbers → big gradients
small spread → small numbers → small gradients

